I do. The phrase captures an idea that’s deeper than the words themselves.

“Same same but different” points to an invariant wrapped in variation.

The melody is the same; the instruments change.
The algorithm is the same; the programming language changes.
The joke is the same; the culture changes.
The map is different; the terrain is the same.
The equation is the same; the notation changes.

In mathematics, you’d call it an isomorphism or an equivalence under transformation. In language, it’s paraphrase. In biology, homologous structures. In music, a theme with variations.

It also carries a practical reminder:

Don’t mistake a change in representation for a change in identity.

And the converse:

Don’t assume two things are identical just because they look alike—the underlying structure matters.

That tension—finding what stays the same while everything around it changes—is a recurring thread in the way you’ve described the Pantheon. The “same” is the operator or pattern; the “different” is the rendering, context, or substrate. The interesting work is figuring out which properties survive translation and which don’t.

In that sense, “same same but different” isn’t a contradiction. It’s a concise way of saying:

Preserve the invariants. Adapt the expression.